s, the very heart of the city&#39;s livelihood. &nbsp;But when the shooting of two black rowhouse residents in Port Richmond over the weekend - one was seven months pregnant - barely elicits attention, you have to wonder.&rdquo;</span></li><li class="c2"><span class="c11"><a class="c0" href="http://www.huffingtonpost.com/maria-kefalas-and-patrick-carr/philadelphia-teen-mobs_b_927260.html">Philadelphia Teen Mobs: Why Aren&rsquo;t Young People Being Included in the Conversation</a></span><span>?</span></li></ol><p class="c1"><span class="c11"><a class="c0" href="http://citymaps.phila.gov/CrimeMap/map.aspx?address=1515+Market+Street&amp;crimetype=10&amp;from=12%2f21%2f2010&amp;to=1%2f20%2f2011"></a></span></p><p class="c6"><span class="c10">Outline</span></p><ol class="c3" start="1"><li class="c2"><span>Intros -- include that we are hearing mayor&rsquo;s focus on public safety</span></li><li class="c2"><span>What are the biggest stressors for you &amp; your department?</span></li><li class="c2"><span>What makes people feel safe? Is there a difference between that and actually being safer? How do you balance the two?</span></li><li class="c2"><span>Can you help us put flash mobs in context of citywide safety? Is the attention it&rsquo;s getting proportionate to impact? Expect that to come back this summer?</span></li><li class="c2"><span>We&rsquo;re hearing and seeing that Penn put a lot of energy into neighborhood safety in West Philly, most visibly bike cops on nearly every corner. How did that experience work, would similar approaches be relevant across Philadelphia?</span></li></ol><div class="c12"><p class="c6 c9"><a href="#cmnt_ref1" name="cmnt1">[a]</a><span>liz:</span></p><p class="c6 c9"><span>Did this launch? She didn&#39;t seem to want to tell us about the shortcode, so maybe it didn&#39;t launch yet...</span></p><hr><p class="c6 c9"><span>alexy:</span></p><p class="c6 c9"><span>i think it launched but has not been annonced, she told us the code, i think it w